Issue.Code:
C#
public void SurfaceChanged(ISurfaceHolder holder, global::Android.Graphics.Format format, int width, int height)
{
    // Set flag to recreate gl surface or rendering can be bad on orienation change or if app 
    // is closed in one orientation and re-opened in another.
    lock (_lockObject)
    {
        // can only be triggered when main loop is running, is unsafe to overwrite other states
        if (_internalState == InternalState.Running_GameThread)
        {
            _internalState = InternalState.ForceRecreateSurface;
        }
    }
}

[SurfaceChanged()](https://github.com/MonoGame/MonoGame/blob/3fde2bf96888ca7e21dc090389e59260a999401a/MonoGame.Framework/Platform/Android/MonoGameAndroidGameView.cs#L104-L117)

The method is indeed getting called, however the _internalState is still InternalState.Resuming_UIThread . Because of this nothing actually happens and the InternalState is never set to ForceRecreateSurface, which needs to happen.

Because the surface never gets recreated the method [MakeCurrent()](https://github.com/MonoGame/MonoGame/blob/3fde2bf96888ca7e21dc090389e59260a999401a/MonoGame.Framework/Platform/Android/MonoGameAndroidGameView.cs#L156-L165) constantly fails and spits out the error 
> eglMakeCurrent:819 error 300b (EGL_BAD_NATIVE_WINDOW)


## Solutions
The way I see it there are 2 possible solutions. 

One would be to implement a system that ensures _internalState will eventually get set to ForceRecreateSurface even if _internalState is not Running_GameThread when SurfaceChanged gets called. I assume this would involve adding some variable such as _needToForceRecreateSurface that __always__ gets set to true in SurfaceChanged and then when _internalState returns to Running_GameThread the state could be set to ForceRecreateSurface by [RunIteration()](https://github.com/MonoGame/MonoGame/blob/3fde2bf96888ca7e21dc090389e59260a999401a/MonoGame.Framework/Platform/Android/MonoGameAndroidGameView.cs#L568-L633)

The second solution would be to simply insert the same code from SurfaceChanged into the MakeCurrent method if the failure occurs. Here's an example of that implementation.
C#
public virtual void MakeCurrent()
{
    EnsureUndisposed();
    if (!egl.EglMakeCurrent(eglDisplay, eglSurface,
            eglSurface, eglContext))
    {
        if (egl.EglGetError() == EGL10.EglBadNativeWindow)
        {
            lock (_lockObject)
            {
                // can only be triggered when main loop is running, is unsafe to overwrite other states
                if (_internalState == InternalState.Running_GameThread)
                {
                    _internalState = InternalState.ForceRecreateSurface;
                }
            }
        }
        System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine("Error Make Current" + GetErrorAsString());
    }
}
`

c#
[CommandLineParameter(
    Name = "build",
    Flag = "b",
    ValueName = "sourceFile",
    Description = "Build the content source file using the previously set switches and options. Optional destination path may be specified with \"sourceFile;destFile\" if you wish to change the output filepath.")
]
public void OnBuild(string sourceFile)
{
    // Make sure the source file is absolute.
    if (!Path.IsPathRooted(sourceFile))
        sourceFile = Path.Combine(Directory.GetCurrentDirectory(), sourceFile);
}


As shown in the snippet above, in the `OnBuild` function, **the full path of the resource is calculated and stored**. Later in the execution, when all the command/configuration has been parsed and the paths full paths have been generated, a loop goes through all the content generating the output files. The same thing happens on the `OnCopy` function.

It makes sense to do it, because if we are building files from different paths, then by the time the actual Build or Copy happens, there is no need to worry about the current directory, as the full paths have been generated in the initial parsing.

The problem comes when referencing an extern assembly by using the `/reference` flag. Contrary to what happens with Build and Copy content, the references full path is never calculated in the parsing phase, so when the times comes to actually load the assemblies, if the place where you are calling mgcb is different from the place where the .mgcb file is, then it won't find the assemblies (unless of course the references path are already a full path).

In this snippet it can be seen that the assembly references are just added as is, and no full path is generated

c#
[CommandLineParameter(
    Name = "reference",
    Flag = "f",
    ValueName = "assembly",
    Description = "Adds an assembly reference for resolving content importers, processors, and writers.")
]

public readonly List<string> References = new List<string>();

bool SetOption(MemberInfo member, string value)
{
    {. . .}
    if (IsList(member))
    {
        // Append this value to a list of options.
        GetList(member).Add(ChangeType(value, ListElementType(member)));
    }
    {. . .}
}
