The problem with this is in any game were you might allow the user to assign or use control group keys.
Strategy games often do this and really any game were you want to allow the user to assign arbitrary hotkeys or control groups.
This is the only monogame way to really do this, as text input isn't made for this idea.

You normally check that any keys are pressed first by getting this method. 
Checking if its length is more then zero you then procced to process the keys pressed instead of checking for every single possible key combination with getstate which would be insane.

Simply calling this method creates garbage.
Since it is a array of keys and keys are structs. It appears to be boxing and unboxing.

The couple methods associated with it have a number of odditys which appear redundant and overly complex. All for the sake of apparently avoiding garbage which it doesn't do.


Ill post my notes i took while looking it over.


        // All three methods associated with GetPressedKeys are heavily using bitwise math to count bits.
        // https://github.com/MonoGame/MonoGame/blob/develop/MonoGame.Framework/Input/KeyboardState.cs
        // The array is returned after being populated in .... KeyboardState.GetPressedKeys.
        // It populates the array primarily by calling  ... AddKeysToArray(uint keys, int offset, Keys[] pressedKeys, int index)
        //
        // 256 bit flags are being stored across 8 32 bit unsigned integers they are being treated as a bit array.
        //
        // Array of 256 bits:
        // uint keys0, keys1, keys2, keys3, keys4, keys5, keys6, keys7;
        //
        // It is based on this which seems out of place here.
        // http://graphics.stanford.edu/~seander/bithacks.html#CountBitsSetParallel
        //
        // The count method is only used so that a keys struct array of the correct length can be created.
        // There is no way for the user to make use of the count even though this has been calculated.
        // It generates garbage by calling the method since this is a array of structs boxing must be occuring.
        // 
`

using System;
