Issue.Description:
When I call graphics.ApplyChanges() while in fullscreen, despite having graphics.IsFullScreen = true, the game reverts back to windowed. This usually happens right when I call .ApplyChanges() again, but may occasionally take more attempts. 

While in this state, the game is effectively windowed, but the .IsFullScreen property is still true. The problem persists until I set .IsFullScreen back to false, apply, set it back to true and apply again. It's especially bothersome when a user tries to change the resolution while in fullscreen, as this action requires an .ApplyChanges() call while already in fullscreen, thus triggering the problem. The only workaround I see for this is to hop to windowed and back, but this looks very ugly.

To replicate, create a new project and add the following to the Game1 class (rewriting the existing functions where necessary):
     
    KeyboardState last_state;

    protected override void Initialize() {
        last_state = Keyboard.GetState();
        base.Initialize();
    }

    protected override void Update(GameTime gameTime) {

        if(Keyboard.GetState().IsKeyDown(Keys.Enter) && !last_state.IsKeyDown(Keys.Enter)) {
            graphics.IsFullScreen = true;
            graphics.ApplyChanges();
        }
        last_state = Keyboard.GetState();

        base.Update(gameTime);
    }

When running the game, pressing Enter the first time will trigger fullscreen as intended. Pressing Enter again (or in some cases, several times) will trigger the problem. The screen is back to windowed and stays there no matter how many times you press Enter.

